The Management of Ikeja Electric Plc said they are in full supports of the ongoing efforts of the National Assembly, in collaboration with the Federal Government on the possibility of providing free electricity for two months as part of Covid-19 palliative for customers. The Head of media of the organisation, Mr Felix Ofulue who stated this in a chat with LEADERSHIP said since the call for free electricity is still on planning stage, customers should pay as when due their electricity bill until everything is put in place. According to him, “However, it is important to point out that at the moment, it is only a proposal and is still undergoing stakeholder reviews on its feasibility. It has not been approved by the Government as a stimulus package or palliative.” Ofulue stated that as the ability of the DisCos to implement this proposed palliative is subject to the stimulus package being passed by the National Assembly and signed into law by Mr. President, Ikeja Discos is awaiting the feasibility from stakeholders. “We urge all our customers to continue to pay their utility bills as usual, while on our part, we shall continue to serve and put our customers first during this difficult period.” 